I'm having the same problem as @ghego1. I'm usually seeing the following error:

7/6/16 10:29:40.605 PM ShipIt[8038]: Installation error: Error Domain=NSPOSIXErrorDomain Code=13 "Permission denied" UserInfo={NSLocalizedDescription=Permission denied}

This search always shows issues popping up regarding non-admin accounts but I am on an admin account and this is happening even inside of my user directory.

Also having the same problem with Electron 1.2.4, 1.2.8, and 1.3.2 on OS X 10.11.5.

I'm seeing an error in the logs:

```
Couldn't remove owned bundle at location file:///var/folders/T/your-bundle.ShipIt/AppName.app, error NSError { domain: NSCocoaErrorDomain, code: 4, description: "“AppName.app” couldn’t be removed.", failureReason: "The file doesn’t exist.", underlying error: NSError { domain: NSPOSIXErrorDomain, code: 2, description: "The operation couldn’t be completed. No such file or directory" }
```

But it then says after that the `Installation completed successfully`, so I don't think it's relevant.

My updater code (based on https://nulab-inc.com/blog/typetalk/3-necessary-things-to-correctly-release-a-product-based-on-the-electron-app/):

```
  autoUpdater.setFeedURL(config.macUpdateUrl + '/' + appVersion);
  autoUpdater.addListener('update-downloaded', function(e, releaseNotes, releaseName, releaseDate, updateURL, quitAndInstall) {
    var index = dialog.showMessageBox(mainWindow, {
      type: 'info',
      buttons: ['Restart', 'Later'],
      message: 'A new version is available! Please restart the app to apply the updates.',
      detail: releaseName + "\n\n" + releaseNotes
    });
    if (index !== 1) {
      quitAndInstall();
    }
  });
  autoUpdater.checkForUpdates();
```

I have a similar issue. The autoUpdater gets stuck at update-available on both Windows 7 and MacOS 10.10.5, Electron 1.3.2). It basically emits that [update-available] event - downloads the update, installs it - and then refuses to proceed. It will not, in any way, fire update-downloaded. The app is fully signed, I tried granting it the proper chown and chmod on Mac, kept it in the Application's folder like a regular user would. Nothing.

I've been banging my head against this for the past 3 days. Any help? My ShipIt_Stderr.log outputs the same as the above: Couldn't remove owned bundle at location ... error NSError code 4, "The File doesn't exist".

If I then shut down the app and relaunch it, manually, it will have successfully updated, as ShipIt in its logs also report that "Installation completed successfully" - "ShipIt quitting". How can I provide my user with a good notification that they should restart, if the events do not propagate properly?

